{"id":"1911.10900","submitter":"Hartmut Hafermann","authors":"Jan-Willem Goossens, Hartmut Hafermann and Yves Jaou\\\"en","title":"Experimental realization of Fermi-Pasta-Ulam-Tsingou recurrence in a\n  long-haul optical fiber transmission system","comments":"Version accepted for publication in Scientific Reports","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1038/s41598-019-54825-4","report-no":null,"categories":"eess.SP nlin.SI physics.optics","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The integrable nonlinear Schr\\\"odinger equation (NLSE) is a fundamental model\nof nonlinear science which also has important consequences in engineering. The\npowerful framework of the periodic inverse scattering transform (IST) provides\na description of the nonlinear phenomena modulational instability and\nFermi-Pasta-Ulam-Tsingou (FPUT) recurrence in terms of exact solutions. It\nassociates the complex nonlinear dynamics with invariant nonlinear spectral\ndegrees of freedom that may be used to encode information. While optical fiber\nis an ideal testing ground of its predictions, maintaining integrability over\nsufficiently long distances to observe recurrence, as well as synthesizing and\nmeasuring the field in both amplitude and phase on the picosecond timescales of\ntypical experiments is challenging. Here we report on the experimental\nrealization of FPUT recurrence in terms of an exact space-time-periodic\nsolution of the integrable NLSE in a testbed for optical communication\nexperiments. The complex-valued initial condition is constructed by means of\nthe finite-gap integration method, modulated onto the optical carrier driven by\nan arbitrary waveform generator and launched into a recirculating fiber loop\nwith periodic amplification. The measurement with an intradyne coherent\nreceiver after a predetermined number of revolutions provides a non-invasive\nfull-field characterization of the space-time dynamics. The recurrent\nspace-time evolution is in close agreement with theoretical predictions over a\ndistance of 9000 km. Nonlinear spectral analysis reveals an invariant nonlinear\nspectrum. The space-time scale exceeds that of previous experiments on FPUT\nrecurrence in fiber by three orders of magnitude.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 25 Nov 2019 13:35:51 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-11-28"}
